---
import DocsLayout from '../../../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import CodeExample from '../../../../components/CodeExample.astro';
import HubCard from '../../../../components/HubCard.astro';

const title = 'Tailwind vs LSCSS';
const description = 'Why utility-first Tailwind CSS conflicts with semantic HTML and long-term maintainability—and how Layered Semantic CSS keeps styling in CSS.';

const tailwindExample = `<article class="p-4 mb-4 bg-white rounded shadow text-center grid gap-4">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold">Product title</h2>
    <p class="text-sm text-muted">Product description</p>
</article>`;

const lscssExample = `<article class="product-card">
    <h2 class="title">Product title</h2>
    <p class="description">Product description</p>
</article>`;

const utilityExample = `.vh
.a11y-link
.a11y-link--focusable`;
---

<DocsLayout
    title={title}
    description={description}
    schemaType="TechArticle"
>
    <article>
        <p class="eyebrow">Comparison</p>

        <h1>
            Tailwind vs LSCSS
        </h1>

        <p>
            Tailwind optimises for shipping screens quickly by putting styling
            in HTML. LSCSS optimises for calm, maintainable systems by keeping
            presentation in CSS and HTML focused on meaning. This site treats
            utility-first markup as a structural mistake—not a neutral style
            preference.
        </p>

        <nav class="section-nav" aria-label="Tailwind and LSCSS comparison sections">
            <a href="#why-utility-first-hurts">Why utility-first hurts</a>
            <a href="#differences">Differences</a>
            <a href="#markup">Markup</a>
            <a href="#utilities">What LSCSS allows</a>
            <a href="#when-tailwind-appears">When teams still pick Tailwind</a>
        </nav>

        <section class="content-block">
            <h2 id="why-utility-first-hurts">
                Why utility-first CSS in HTML is a problem
            </h2>

            <ul>
                <li>
                    <strong>Not semantic.</strong>
                    Markup should describe structure and intent, not padding scales
                    and flex direction.
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>HTML bloat.</strong>
                    Every element carries a styling vocabulary instead of a role.
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Hard to scan.</strong>
                    Reviews and debugging mean decoding class lists, not reading
                    components.
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Architecture in the wrong place.</strong>
                    Design decisions live in templates, spread across hundreds of
                    files, with no single owner for “what a card is”.
                </li>
                <li>
                    <strong>Debt compounds.</strong>
                    Repeated utility stacks are unnamed components; changing a
                    pattern means find-and-replace across markup, not one CSS file.
                </li>
            </ul>

            <p>
                Tailwind is disciplined about <em>which</em> utilities exist. That
                does not fix the model: styling still belongs in CSS layers and
                named components, not on every node.
            </p>
        </section>

        <section class="content-block">
            <h2 id="differences">
                Main differences
            </h2>

            <ul>
                <li>Tailwind: utility classes in markup as the primary styling system.</li>
                <li>LSCSS: semantic components, modifiers, state, and theme in CSS.</li>
                <li>Tailwind: less custom CSS, more class composition in HTML.</li>
                <li>LSCSS: calmer HTML; ownership and overrides live in layers.</li>
                <li>Tailwind: optimises short-term delivery.</li>
                <li>LSCSS: optimises long-term readability and team handover.</li>
            </ul>
        </section>

        <section class="content-block">
            <h2 id="markup">
                Markup comparison
            </h2>

            <p>
                Typical utility-first markup:
            </p>

            <CodeExample code={tailwindExample} language="html" />

            <p>
                It is explicit about styling and fast to type. It is also noisy,
                non-semantic, and tiring to maintain once the product grows.
            </p>

            <p>
                The LSCSS-shaped alternative:
            </p>

            <CodeExample code={lscssExample} language="html" />

            <p>
                Structure stays readable; CSS owns how the card looks, including
                responsive and theme behaviour, without polluting the template.
            </p>
        </section>

        <section class="content-block">
            <h2 id="utilities">
                What LSCSS allows (not utility-first)
            </h2>

            <p>
                LSCSS has a <code>utilities</code> layer. That does
                <strong>not</strong> mean “use Tailwind-style classes everywhere”.
                It means a tiny set of universal helpers—mostly accessibility:
            </p>

            <CodeExample code={utilityExample} />

            <p>
                Spacing, layout, colour, and typography belong in components,
                layout, or theme. If a cluster of utilities keeps repeating, it
                was always a component.
            </p>
        </section>

        <section class="content-block">
            <h2 id="when-tailwind-appears">
                When teams still pick Tailwind
            </h2>

            <p>
                Prototypes, short-lived marketing pages, and teams that prioritise
                speed over maintainability sometimes accept utility-first cost. That
                is a business choice, not evidence that utility CSS is good
                architecture.
            </p>

            <p>
                LSCSS fits better when:
            </p>

            <ul>
                <li>the site or app will live for years</li>
                <li>many people touch the same CSS and HTML</li>
                <li>semantic structure and accessibility matter</li>
                <li>you are tired of refactoring class soup</li>
            </ul>
        </section>

        <section class="content-block">
            <h2>
                Next useful pages
            </h2>

            <div class="hub-grid">
                <HubCard href="/apply/methodology/" title="Core methodology">
                <p>Layers, naming, and ownership without utility-first markup.</p>
            </HubCard>

                <HubCard href="/apply/utilities/" title="Utilities">
                <p>What rare helpers are allowed—and what should never be a utility.</p>
            </HubCard>

                <HubCard href="/apply/examples/" title="Examples">
                <p>Before/after: utility overload vs semantic components.</p>
            </HubCard>
            </div>
        </section>

        <p>
            This comparison reflects lived delivery experience: utility-first
            can ship fast; semantic layered CSS stays understandable. LSCSS
            chooses the second on purpose.
        </p>
    </article>
</DocsLayout>
